Over the past century, global temperatures has increased by ∼0.74 °C, and one of the most important bioclimatic effects seems to be an increase in the mean surface temperature (
 Stocker et al. 2013). Therefore, assessing species’ responses to climate change is one of the greatest challenges that conservation biologists face. Notwithstanding, the effects of raising temperatures have been felt from species to community levels (
 Pounds et al. 1999; 
 Walther et al. 2002; 
 Thomas et al. 2004). Hence, identifying the most vulnerable species or group of species likely to be affected by changing climatic conditions is the first appropriate step in mitigating the impacts on biodiversity.
